##How are medical staff infected in the fight against new crown pneumonia?

“

During the outbreak of SARS, 996 cases were infected by medical staff in China, accounting for 18.8% of all clinically diagnosed cases.

”

At 10:30 am on February 18, after all efforts to rescue the invalid, Wuhan Wuchang Hospital Director Liu Zhiming died of new pneumonia in Tongji hospital, Zhongfa Xincheng district. Liu Zhiming was the first serving dean to die of an epidemic of new Crown Infections. The infection and death of the medical staff will directly affect the public's confidence in the fight against the epidemic and the supplement of the following medical treatment.

As of 2400 hours on February 11, a total of 1,716 cases have been reported among medical personnel in China, of which 1,502 cases have been reported in Hubei Province, accounting for 87.5% of the total.

However, in another report, the number of confirmed cases by medical personnel was even higher.

As of February 11,2020, the number of cases of acute pneumonia in the United States had increased by 20 percent, according to a new pneumonia study published Feb. 17 in the Chinese Journal of Epidemiology by the COVID-19, of the 422 institutions providing care for patients with NCP, 3,019 staff members were infected with COVID-19 pneumonia (1,716 confirmed) , of whom 5 died, with a crude case fatality rate of 0.3% .

In the article, 1,688 medical workers with severe illness were diagnosed, mainly in Wuhan (64%) and other parts of Hubei (23.3%) . So far, the paper says, there is no evidence of a superspreader incident at any of the facilities that serve patients with COVID-19 pneumonia. However, the causes of infection among medical staff and the failure of prevention remain to be further investigated.

In an interview with CCTV, Jiao Yahui, deputy director of the medical and Health Administration Bureau of the National Health Commission, explained the difference between the two cases of infection among health care workers. "There are health care workers who are infected with the new coronavirus in hospitals and at work, and there are health care workers who may have been infected with the new coronavirus in their families or communities, so it can not be said that these health care workers were infected at work, it can not be said that these people were infected because of inadequate protection. Of course, there were a lot of cases of infection among health care workers in the early days because of poor protection."

During the SARS outbreak, medical personnel were also the most concentrated area of infection occupation.

During the SARS outbreak in March 2003, medical staff accounted for one-third of the 305 SARS cases first reported in Guangdong Province. From November 2002 to August 5,2003,996 cases were reported among health care workers in China, accounting for 18.8% of all clinically diagnosed cases, according to a SARS epidemiology report from public health.

In 2004, Tao Maoxuan of the Center for Disease Control and Prevention and the Institute of Environmental and Health Related Product Safety published in occupational and health, an analysis of risk factors for Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome among health care workers, the number of layers of isolation clothing, the number of masks worn, whether the mask is worn, whether the hand-washing device is non-contact type, whether the initial contact patients wear masks, whether they participate in sputum aspiration, etc. .

At the same time, the article said, there is no clear division of infectious disease wards, making it possible for SARS to spread within wards. "In this survey, it was found that some hospitals used air conditioning in wards, waiting rooms and offices, but if used improperly, it could easily lead to cross-infection. Therefore, during the SARS epidemic, it was necessary to ban the use of common air conditioning in all areas of the hospital."

In addition, Huang Jinshui and others said in "a preliminary study of the causes of SARS infection among medical staff" that prolonged exposure to polluted environment and failure of medical staff to obtain information on the epidemic situation in a timely manner also contributed to the causes of SARS infection among medical staff, "early detection, early reporting, early isolation and early treatment of the epidemic can be achieved by medical personnel. On the other hand, it can enable medical personnel to take timely and effective measures to fully protect themselves and reduce their chances of being infected. In the early days of the SARS epidemic, more health care workers in Guangdong Province were infected, and an important external cause was the failure of health care workers to obtain timely information about the epidemic."
